PROMPT 93: What are the inspection requirements for temporary support systems during bridge construction?
======================================================================
RESPONSE:
- Inspect and maintain temporary works in an acceptable condition.
- Perform an in-depth inspection of the temporary works in the presence of the COno more than 24 hours before starting each concrete placement, or before allowing people to enter a coffe...[[SRC_1]]- Discontinue concrete placement and take corrective action if settlement or deflections occur that deviate more than ⅜ inch from those shown on the approved drawings.
- Record settlement to the nearest ⅛ inch during concrete placement.
- Do not use the ground surface near falsework supports as a reference elevation.- Provide tell-tales with surveyed measurements, or other acceptable means, for accuratemeasurement of falsework settlement.
- All panel points are on the true curve.
- A true curve by more than ½ inch at any point; and (c) All panel points are on the true curve.[[SRC_1]]- Temporary or re-commissioned bridges used as detours and in-service longer than 90 days shall be subject to full National Bridge Inspection Standards (all SI&A data; ex., NBIS inspection, load ratings, and scour evaluation).
- All SI&A data shall be submitted to the Washington State NBI database within 90 days of opening to vehicular traffic.
- An open bridge is defined as a bridge that is near substantial completion with general highway traffic accessing/operating on the bridge in its final planned configuration.
- Phased construction stages, if carrying traffic for 90 days or longer shall meet theserequirements.
- Bridges open less than 90 days will need regular safety-type inspections to ensure safe operation of traffic.[[SRC_2]]- The Project Engineer shall see that the falsework and forms are constructed in accordance with the submitted plans.
- If it becomes necessary, or the Contractor desires to deviate from the submitted plans, a revised plan for review shall be submitted and the Contractor shall not startconstruction in accordance with the revised plan until the review is complete.
- All revisions to the plan shall be reviewed by the State Bridge and StructuresEngineer (or Terminal Design Engineer) to ensure the structural integrity of the falsework and formwork.[[SRC_4]]- Temporary bridges shall be designed to meet the requirement of BDM Section 10.13and other BDM Sections as applicable.
- Bridges shall be configured to allow inspectors direct access to bearings, and access to within 3-feet of superstructure surfaces.
- See also Figure 2.3.11-1 for under-bridge-inspection-truck clearance requirements.- Adequate clearance for maintenance and inspection of bearings shall be provided. The clearance shall be adequate to inspect, remove and replace the bearings.
- Jacking points shall be provided for bearing replacement. Jacking points shall bedesigned to support 200 percent of the calculated lifting load.
- Built-up plate girder bridges with girders 5-feet deep or greater in depth shallbe detailed with safety handrails for inspectors walking the bottom flanges.
- At large gusset plate locations on truss bridges (3-feet wide or wider), cables or lanyard anchor...[[SRC_5]]- The temporary bridge(s) shall be shown on the Bridge Preliminary Plan and shallinclude the minimum required length and minimum roadway width, including shoulders.
- The approaches to a temporary bridge, including but not limited to, slopes and reinforced slopes, shall be designed in accordance with Chapter 8 and the Geotechnical Design Manual.
- The Contractor shall maintain the temporary bridge, including the driving surface, throughout its service life.[[SRC_6]]

